<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">Principles: Life and Work</span>
    <span class="post-date">Ray Dalio</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>Reading this for the decision-making systems more than the billionaire mythology. The idea of writing down principles, testing them against reality, and refining them over time fits how I want to approach work and life.</p>
    <p>Chapter 1 frames life as a long sequence of choices where reality keeps giving feedback. Dalio's point is to meet those moments clearly, learn from them, and keep improving how you decide.</p>
    <blockquote class="book-quote">
      <p>"Time is like a river that carries us forward into encounters with reality that require us to make decisions. We can't stop our movement down this river and we can't avoid those encounters. We can only approach them in the best possible way."</p>
      <cite>Chapter 1, Principles: Life and Work</cite>
    </blockquote>
    <p>Chapter 2 turns more personal, with Dalio tracing pieces of his own life and early lessons from work and markets. Later, the book sharpens those lessons into the 5-Step Process:</p>
    <ol class="chapter-notes">
      <li>Have clear goals.</li>
      <li>Identify problems.</li>
      <li>Diagnose root causes.</li>
      <li>Design a plan.</li>
      <li>Execute the plan.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">&#128214; Progress: starting | Theme: systems for decisions</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#principles</span>
    <span class="tag">#career</span>
    <span class="tag">#decision-making</span>
  </div>
</article>

