<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">The Top 10 Distinctions Between Millionaires and the Middle Class</span>
    <span class="post-date">Keith Cameron Smith</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>A short mindset book about the habits and thinking patterns that separate wealth-building behavior from paycheck-to-paycheck comfort.</p>
    <ol class="chapter-notes">
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 1: Millionaires think long-term; the middle class thinks short-term.</strong><br>
        Build toward decade-level freedom instead of optimizing only for this month's comfort.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 2: Millionaires talk about ideas; the middle class talks about things and other people.</strong><br>
        Spend more energy on possibilities, plans, and useful questions than gossip or status objects.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 3: Millionaires embrace change; the middle class is threatened by change.</strong><br>
        Treat change as terrain to adapt to, not a threat to hide from.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 4: Millionaires take calculated risks; the middle class is afraid to take risks.</strong><br>
        Risk is not recklessness; it is making informed bets with upside.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 5: Millionaires continually learn and grow; the middle class thinks learning ended with school.</strong><br>
        School ends, but the upgrade loop should not.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 6: Millionaires work for profits; the middle class works for wages.</strong><br>
        Learn how value, ownership, and upside work instead of only trading hours for wages.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 7: Millionaires believe they must be generous; the middle class believes it can't afford to give.</strong><br>
        Giving is part of an abundance mindset, not something to postpone forever.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 8: Millionaires have multiple sources of income; the middle class has only one or two.</strong><br>
        One source of income is fragile; several aligned sources create optionality.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 9: Millionaires focus on increasing their net worth; the middle class focuses on increasing its paychecks.</strong><br>
        Paychecks matter, but assets and retained value decide long-term strength.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Chapter 10: Millionaires ask themselves empowering questions; middle-class people ask themselves disempowering questions.</strong><br>
        Better questions create better choices, especially under pressure.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
  <div class="post-mood">&#9733;&#9733;&#9733;&#9733;&#9734;</div>
  <div class="post-tags">
    <span class="tag">#finance</span>
    <span class="tag">#mindset</span>
    <span class="tag">#wealth</span>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">Unfu*k Yourself: Get Out of Your Head and into Your Life</span>
    <span class="post-date">Gary John Bishop</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>Bishop frames life like a train that never stops. You can glance back at where you have been, but the train keeps moving. Some days the window shows nothing but rain and grey sky. Other days you roll through something breathtaking. The point is: you do not control the scenery, but you are always moving forward, and the view will change if you let it.</p>
  </div>
